<p>In <a href="http://christophergandrud.blogspot.de/2012/06/data-on-github-easy-way-to-make-your.html">previous</a> <a href="http://christophergandrud.blogspot.kr/2012/06/update-to-data-on-github-post-solution.html">posts</a> I described how to input data stored on <a href="https://github.com/">GitHub</a> directly into <strong>R</strong>. </p>

<p>You can do the same thing with source code stored on <strong>GitHub</strong>. <a href="http://had.co.nz/">Hadley Wickham</a> has actually made the whole process easier by combining the <code>getURL</code>, <code>textConnection</code>, and <code>source</code> commands into one function: <code>source_url</code>. This is in his <a href="https://github.com/hadley/devtools/">devtools</a> package.</p>

<p>Imagine we have a .R source code file like this:</p>

<pre><code># Make cars scatter plot
library(ggplot2)
Plot &lt;- qplot(cars$dist, cars$speed) +
            theme_bw()
print(Plot)
</code></pre>

<p>It is hosted on <strong>GitHub</strong> with the URL: <a href="https://raw.github.com/christophergandrud/christophergandrud.github.com/master/SourceCode/CarsScatterExample.R">https://raw.github.com/christophergandrud/christophergandrud.github.com/master/SourceCode/CarsScatterExample.R</a></p>

<p>So to run this source code directly in <strong>R</strong> all we need to type is:</p>

<pre><code class="r">library(devtools)
SourceURL &lt;- &quot;https://raw.github.com/christophergandrud/christophergandrud.github.com/master/SourceCode/CarsScatterExample.R&quot;
source_url(SourceURL)
</code></pre>

<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="plot of chunk CarsPlot"/> </p>

<p>There you go. </p>

<p>You can also directly source <a href="https://gist.github.com/">GitHub gists</a> (which are nice for sharing short bits of code) with the <code>source_gist</code> command.</p>
